[1
Date: May 22, 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AP [edited
<http://farmbid.com/newsandweather/nw_news_view.asp?id=175632>
European Union commissioner proposes new mad cow measures
---------------------------------------------
BRUSSELS, Belgium: The European Union's consumer protection and health
chief unveiled new proposals on Tuesday to deal with the mad cow crisis,
including lowering the minimum testing age for cattle to 24 months and
testing sheep. EU commissioner David Byrne also proposed halting the
automatic slaughter of entire herds [in which cases of bovine spongiform
encephalopathy (BSE) are uncovered. Addressing an EU meeting of the 15 farm
ministers, Byrne said the moves were necessary transition measures ahead of
the adoption on 1 July of the new EU regulation on transmissible spongiform
encephalopathy (TSE) diseases, including BSE and scrapie, which affects sheep.
Byrne also wants to extend the current EU ban on the use of meat and bone
meal in animal feed -- blamed largely for the two major outbreaks of BSE
that have swept across the EU -- and introduce stricter controls on imports
of animal feed from non-EU countries where "potential weaknesses" currently
exist. Testing for TSEs will focus on healthy slaughtered animals and
animals that die on the farm.
The EU has struggled to deal with a health crisis that has undermined
consumer confidence and underscored the need for more adequate controls and
test methods. Since an intensive BSE testing program began in all EU member
states on 1 Jan 2001, 75 cases of the disease have been uncovered among the
1.75 million tests carried out on healthy animals before slaughter. More
than 80 cases of BSE have been diagnosed as a result of testing dead, sick,
or injured animals.
Byrne said good veterinary surveillance was the single most important
method of detecting BSE, and chided several member states for a lack of
proper controls. While backing the lowering of the testing age for BSE in
sick, injured, or dead animals to 24 months, Byrne said he would favor a
reduction in the current 30 month old testing age to 18 months, or even 12
months, if it helped boost consumer confidence.
The Italian health ministry on Tuesday confirmed its 15th case of mad cow
disease since the EU imposed mandatory testing.
