Date: Wed, 16 May 2001 10:35:42 -0400
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhua News Agency via COMTEX [edited

New cases of mad cow disease detected in France
--------------------------------------------------
PARIS, May 15, 2001: The French Ministry of Agriculture Tuesday confirmed 2
new cases of mad cow disease in the provinces of La Manche and Rhone.
France has registered 317 animals with bovine spongiform encephalopathy
since 1991, of which 75 have been detected since the beginning of this
year, according to the Ministry.
******
[3
Date: 18 May 2001
From: ProMEDmail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Associated Press [edited
<http://www.nytimes.com/aponline/world/AP-France-Mad-Cow-Report.html?searc>

PARIS: A report on the handling of risk factors in the outbreak of mad cow
disease lambasts France's Agriculture Ministry for dragging its feet in
forbidding meat-based animal feed and keeping quiet about suspicions. The
report by a Senate commission, released Thursday, predicts that France will
see 300 cases of what is thought to be the human form of the disease in the
next 60 years, a length of time that accounts for the decades-long
incubation period of variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (vCJD). So far, 3
people have died [of vCJD in France. "The risk is now behind us, even if
the consequences lie ahead," said the 362 page report, released after a 6
month investigation.
Interministerial reports from 1994-2000 "show that the Agriculture Ministry
constantly tried to hinder or delay precautionary measures, which later
proved to be security measures, under the motive that they had no
scientific bases," the report said. Agriculture Minister Jean Glavany
denounced the report as "completely false" and said it amounted to a
"political maneuver."
Among the evidence, the report cites an official in the Agriculture
Ministry, Regis Lesueur, saying that "some partial information" showed as
early as 1994 a possible link between bovine spongiform encephalopathy and
the human brain-wasting illness. The report says that there was sufficient
reason before 1996 to ban livestock feed made from animal carcasses that
could carry the malady. Animal feed made from meat and bone was banned for
cows in 1990, but not for pigs and sheep, the report points out. Mix-ups
could have occurred in factories, in trucks, or at farms where both types
of animals are raised, the report suggested. Such "cross contamination
seems to constitute the most plausible explanation of the second phase of
bovine contamination," after 1996, the report said.
The commission has all but dismissed claims that mad cow disease continued
propagating in France because of the illicit importing from Britain of
banned feed. A National Assembly commission is to release a report on the
issue in June.
--
