[6
Date: 17 May 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Irish News [edited
<http://www.irishnews.com/current/thegreenpage4.html>

Thousands of cattle and sheep were slaughtered and then burned or buried as
agriculture officials in the [Irish Republic, Northern Ireland, and
Britain struggled to restrict the spread of foot and mouth disease (FMD).
Farming areas and workers were afflicted, and tourism suffered a major blow
as holidaymakers steered clear of Ireland and Britain. It was suggested
that the burning mounds were causing more pollution in Britain than all its
industrial stacks.
Now a company based in Clydebank, Scotland believes it can help [to limit
the damage done to our environment by pyres of FMD or bovine spongiform
encephalopathy (BSE)-infected livestock. In recent week, Ken Stuart of
Waste Reduction Europe Ltd (WRE) visited Northern Ireland to discuss new
technology with agriculture and environment officials which would eradicate
the pathogens in cattle diagnosed with BSE.
WRE has developed a tissue digestor, [which eliminates the need for
incineration and the release of potentially dangerous pollutants and
[infectious agents. The digestor works like a pressure cooker. It operates
at 150 degrees Celsius, and converts animal tissues into an aqueous
solution which, the company claims, can be "safely disposed of in a sewer".
The process uses alkaline hydrolysis at an elevated temperature to convert
the proteins, nucleic acids, and lipids of all cells and tissues, as well
as the infectious microorganisms, to a sterile solution. The manufacturer
argues that, unlike incinerators or pyres, their "environmentally
responsible" process releases no emission to the atmosphere, operates at a
fraction of the cost, destroys all pathogens, and reduces the volume of the
carcass by up to 98 per cent.
Researchers have discovered that traces of prions -- proteins responsible
for BSE -- could survive the incineration process, leaving an end product
that remains a biohazard. Ken Stuart said that the WRE digestors were
already being used on a trial basis in England and Scotland and that the
company is currently awaiting legislation to go through the EU system and
allow full time use of its technology. WRE is a subsidiary of a giant waste
reduction company in the United States. The digestor system was invented by
2 US academics who were trying to find ways of disposing of radioactive
laboratory mice. Mr Stuart said the US government had already approved the
system and a number of digestors currently operated in veterinary and
medical schools and universities.
[Byline: Valerie Robinson
